mushrooms <- read_csv("https://www.dropbox.com/s/jk5q3dq1u63ey1e/mushrooms.csv?dl=1",

Part One: A perfect tree

mushroom_recipe <- recipe(class ~ ., 
                     data = mushrooms)

tree_mod <- decision_tree() %>%
  set_engine("rpart") %>%
  set_mode("classification")

tree_wflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(mushroom_recipe) %>%
  add_model(tree_mod) %>% 
  fit(mushrooms)
#Determine that accuracy is nearly 100 percent!

tree_fitted <- tree_wflow %>% 
   pull_workflow_fit()
## Warning: `pull_workflow_fit()` was deprecated in workflows 0.2.3.
## Please use `extract_fit_parsnip()` instead.
rpart.plot(tree_fitted$fit)

Nature Guide

  1. If the Odor of a mushroom does not smell like almonds, anise, or has no odor, it is most likely a poisonous mushroom. These scents include: fishy, foul, or musty.

  2. If the odor of a mushroom does smell like one of those options above, you have to move onto spore-print-color.

  3. If the spore-print-color is black=k,brown=n,buff=b,chocolate=h,green=r,orange=o,purple=u,white=w,yellow=y, you are most likely fine to eat it. If it is not one of these, it is poisonous.

Part Two: or is it?

Q1: Cross validation

mushrooms_cvs <- vfold_cv(mushrooms, v = 5)

mushroom_recipe <- recipe(class ~ ., 
                     data = mushrooms)

tree_wflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(mushroom_recipe) %>%
  add_model(tree_mod)

tree_fit <- tree_wflow %>% 
  fit_resamples(mushrooms_cvs)

tree_fit %>% 
  collect_metrics()
## # A tibble: 2  6
##   .metric  .estimator  mean     n  std_err .config             
##   <chr>    <chr>      <dbl> <int>    <dbl> <chr>               
## 1 accuracy binary     0.994     5 0.000925 Preprocessor1_Model1
## 2 roc_auc  binary     0.994     5 0.000954 Preprocessor1_Model1

The classification rules we learned in Part One probably apply to all mushrooms because this model is not overfit, but it does have an extremely high accuracy of 99.4% when cross-validated.

Q2: Bagging

mushrooms_twoplus <- mushrooms %>% 
  select(-`gill_attachment`, -`veil_type`)

mushrooms_twoplus_cvs <- vfold_cv(mushrooms_twoplus, v = 5)

tree_spec <- bag_tree() %>%
  set_engine("rpart", times = 25) %>%
  set_mode("classification")

mushroom_recipe <- recipe(class ~ ., 
                     data = mushrooms_twoplus)

bag_tree_wflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(mushroom_recipe) %>%
  add_model(tree_spec)

tree_fit <- bag_tree_wflow %>% 
  fit_resamples(mushrooms_twoplus_cvs)

tree_fit %>% 
  collect_metrics()
## # A tibble: 2  6

## 1 accuracy binary         1     5       0 Preprocessor1_Model1
## 2 roc_auc  binary         1     5       0 Preprocessor1_Model1

This model is overfit because we see the accuracy and roc_auc as exactly 1 so it would not be successful predicting on new data.

Q4: Neural Networks

  hidden_units(c(2, 12)),
  penalty(c(-5, 0)),
  levels = 3)

  penalty = tune(),
  epochs = 100,
  activation = "linear"

  set_engine("nnet") %>%
  set_mode("classification")

Part Three: Logistic Regression

We used odor and spore_print_color as out indicator variables because our tree outputted these as the two most important variables in predicting poisonous mushrooms. Given that our logistic regression model with only these two variables was still extremely high in accuracy, our conclusion that these are two of the most important variables in considering the poison level of the mushrooms is supported.

log_mod <- logistic_reg() %>%
  set_mode("classification") %>%
  set_engine("glm")

mushroom_recipe <- recipe(class ~ odor + spore_print_color, 
                     data = mushrooms_twoplus)

log_wflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(mushroom_recipe) %>%
  add_model(log_mod)

tree_fit <- log_wflow %>% 
  fit_resamples(mushrooms_twoplus_cvs)
## ! Fold1: preprocessor 1/1, model 1/1: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0...

The single decision tree is obviously not very accurate in predicted customer class, shown by the 40% accuracy rate but the Gini Index is relatively low which indicates relatively high node purity.
